403→                    
404→                           A reverse <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Littlewood%E2%80%93Offord_problem" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">Littlewood-Offord problem</a>. Erdős originally asked this with $\sqrt{2}$ replaced by $1$, but Carnielli and Carolino <a href="#cite-CaCa11-395" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('CaCa11','395'); return false;">[CaCa11]</a> observed that this is false, choosing $z_1=1$ and $z_k=i$ for $2\leq k\leq n$, where $n$ is even, since then the sum is at least $\sqrt{2}$ always.<br><br>Solved in the affirmative by He, Juškevičius, Narayanan, and Spiro <a href="#cite-HJNS24-395" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('HJNS24','395'); return false;">[HJNS24]</a>. The bound of $1/n$ is the best possible, as shown by taking $z_k=1$ for $1\leq k\leq n/2$ and $z_k=i$ otherwise. <br><br>See also <a href="/498" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[498]</a>.
